@condew6103 "they just storyboard the special effects they'll use". I'm not sure CGI has to suck. But it has to serve a purpose. If you're generating 1000 shots in a warehouse, it risks having a workflow that loses the CGI conveying a precise meaning. If the CGI is trying to trick the human brain into being excited, then it's sound and fury signifying nothing.

People remember lines or iconic scenes, but they don't remember thousands of moments that added up. The line was delivered in the context of a movie that meant something. Even without character work, films might have had striking atmospheres. If a line is a function of the danger a character is in, then losing the atmosphere might mean a line can only fail. Similarly, special effects aren't necessarily visual poetry. A director creating shots in reality can make sure that composition always checks out. If you have 10,000 special effects shots, then some may be pure spectacle rather than meaning something - an external representation of something inside the character.

In star wars, you had tatooine. Superficially it's a desert planet. But it's a representation of boredom. The second sun is likely just about creating an exotic environment. If you filmed Tatooine today with most of the shot on a greenscreen, then maybe the artists screw up and try to make the backdrop grand. Then Luke being bored in a place that's violently interesting might be a problem.

